      "id":"artanddesign/2013/oct/06/art-under-attack-tate-review",
      "sectionId":"artanddesign",
      "sectionName":"Art and design",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T23:05:11Z",
      "webTitle":"Art Under Attack: Histories of British Iconoclasm – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/06/art-under-attack-tate-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/06/art-under-attack-tate-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"28",
        "trailText":"<p>A fascinating exploration of physical attacks on paintings and sculptures demonstrates the power of art to provoke fear and loathing, writes <strong>Laura Cumming</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Art Under Attack: Histories of British Iconoclasm – review",
        "body":"<p>An image, wrote <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer\" title=\"\">Albrecht Dürer</a>, \"is no more responsible for superstitious abuse than a weapon is responsible for a murder\". Don't blame the gun, blame the homicidal lunatic who fires it – Dürer's argument about art, more than 500 years ago, is strangely similar to that of the US gun lobby today. Images are not inherently dangerous, he claims, they do not have the power to rouse people to passion, still less idolatry or violence. Only a maniac or a criminal would attack a work of art.</p><p>It is easy to see the logic of this view, which is still prevalent. After all, its dark obverse is that any work of art that has suffered some kind of assault may have provoked or deserved it. The attack occurred because the sculpture unhinged him; the picture terrified her; the portrait looked at her in the wrong way.</p><p>And oddly enough, when someone savaged the eyes of <a href=\"http://www.pinakothek.de/en/albrecht-duerer/self-portrait-fur-trimmed-robe\" title=\"\">Dürer's great 1500 self-portrait</a> in 1905, the museum authorities took precisely this line. Why were the eyes attacked, they asked in the annual report, if not because of the way they looked at the attacker \"with their alarmingly penetrating stare\"?</p><p>Art Under Attack – the subject of <a href=\"http://www.tate.org.uk/about/press-office/press-releases/art-under-attack-histories-british-iconoclasm\" title=\"\">this riveting show</a> at Tate Britain – begins with iconoclasm and ends with destruction as \"an act of creation\" (think <a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/imgres?imgurl=http://artobserved.com/artimages/2013/06/1_Sad-presentiments-of-what-must-come-to-pass.jpg&amp;imgrefurl=http://artobserved.com/2013/06/new-york-jake-and-dinos-chapman-insult-to-injury-at-yoshii-gallery-through-june-29th-2013/&amp;h=1024&amp;w=1225&amp;sz=525&amp;tbnid=WLyZa9Q92frNEM:&amp;tbnh=90&amp;tbnw=108&amp;prev=/search%3Fq%3Djake%2Band%2Bdinos%2Bchapman%2Bgoya%26tbm%3Disch%26tbo%3Du&amp;zoom=1&amp;q=jake+and+dinos+chapman+goya&amp;usg=__OW2FqV7TEDy6z4-9x4AKo1-27xk=&amp;docid=UhA-4IqYG2r8AM&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=oxRLUrSmCKqY0QWqnYHoBA&amp;ved=0CEAQ9QEwAw\" title=\"\">Jake and Dinos Chapman</a>). This last section feels irrelevant and entirely unnecessary. The impulse to attack works of art is so various, so common, so inconsistent and bizarre the curators could have devoted many more galleries to the history of destruction and still not reached the end of their exploration.</p><p>Iconoclasm proper, for instance, involves the purging of religious images. If militant Protestants believed that graven images were sinful, idolatrous, that they might lead to lasting damnation, you'd think they might have been more comprehensive in their appalling destructiveness.</p><p>But though the show is full of tortured medieval figures – Jesus beheaded, Joseph blinded, the Virgin's nose hacked from her face – these sculptures remain unimpeachably recognisable. Christ in Majesty (particularly targeted, it seems, during the reign of His Majesty Henry VIII) may have lost his head, but the absence of the right arm holding the book and the enthroned pose immediately identify the sculpture to the faithful.</p><p>And looking at the magnificent limestone sculpture of the <a href=\"http://www.tate.org.uk/about/press-office/press-releases/statue-dead-christ-on-loan-first-time-tate-britain-mercers-hall\" title=\"\">Dead Christ</a>, which was only discovered last century in the ground beneath the Mercers' Hall in London, one wonders if something in the art itself held the iconoclasts back. The body lies upon its bier, the size of life and fully as profound, poor mouth agape and stone blood freezing in the wounds. The feet, the arms and the crown of thorns are gone, but the attackers did no more damage to the face.</p><p>Iconoclasm suggests extreme violence and, sure enough, there are wild axe marks and frenzied stabbings in this show. It took brute force to lop the hands off a stone Christ – and just think how extraordinary that the perpetrators were Christians themselves – but the damage could also be laboriously programmatic.</p><p>The show contains a contemporary painting of the 1644 destruction in Canterbury Cathedral – workers methodically shattering the high windows with pikes while Puritans in tall hats keep a strict clock-watch below. Pews were used to fuel the furnace in which the lead traceries were melted down, statues were chunked for reuse as masonry; the recycling was ruthlessly efficient.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419112053'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/10/2/1380725482234/Statue-of-the-Dead-Christ-010.jpg' alt='Statue of the Dead Christ from the Mercers' Company.' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>‘The size of life and fully as profound’: Statue of the Dead Christ from the Mercers' Hall, London. Photograph: Marcus Leith and Andrew Dunkley</figcaption></figure><p>And yet at the same time the eyes of religious figures were being scratched out of paintings or gouged from statues specifically so that they could no longer make contact with worshippers. Eyes were regarded as having the power to move. Orders were given to \"utterly extinct and destroy\" such images \"so that there remains no memory of same\". No memory, no vision – nothing to affect the viewer.</p><p>Iconoclasm, vandalism: these are held to be abnormal, philistine, superstitious or as crazy as Dürer might have it. But the middle sections of this show test all these beliefs. The toppling of public statues, for instance, is practically a political tradition the world over.</p><p>Who would puzzle over the felling of George III's statue in America during the war of independence or the eventual removal – after a century of bearing down from a great height – of Nelson's statue in Dublin? Who does not understand the potency of painting the leader's hands red, giving him horns, or putting a placard round his neck to make him apologise? None of this seems remotely aberrant.</p><p>The motive for destructive acts is rarely philistine either. Sometimes the violence is even committed by artists themselves in defence of art. <a href=\"http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/carl-andre-648\" title=\"\">Carl Andre</a>'s <em>Equivalent VIII</em> was attacked by a painter who thought that modern art ought to be better than bricks; Damien Hirst's <em>Away From the Flock</em> – the lamb in formaldehyde – was stained with black ink as a form of creative \"improvement\" by another artist.</p><p>And <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/sculptors/12802.shtml\" title=\"\">Reg Butler</a>'s <a href=\"http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/butler-final-maquette-for-the-unknown-political-prisoner-l01102\" title=\"\"><em>Unknown Political Prisoner</em></a> was attacked by a Hungarian who believed that if the prisoner represented the suffering of real people during the second world war then he ought to be made out of something more dignified than scrap metal. Reg Butler ought to start over. The protest was matched to the motive.</p><p>Each of these instances makes one think again about the nature of art and of our relationship with it; this is what makes Art Under Attack so vividly stimulating. Of course the show has its exceptions. When <a href=\"http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/yale/summary/v013/13.2otten.html\" title=\"\">Mary Wood</a> slashed John Singer Sargent's portrait of Henry James in 1914, the attack had nothing to do with (and nothing to say about) either the artist or the writer, whose books she had not read, and it's not obvious that it furthered the suffragette cause in any way. Nor are the documents and photographs interesting.</p><p>On the other hand, the very fact that Wood attacked a portrait – and not, say, a landscape – has its peculiar&nbsp;significance. When it comes&nbsp;to iconoclasm, the damage is almost always done to representations&nbsp;of people as if they were surrogate persons.</p><p>To attack images as if they were real or alive – it sounds the most primitive of instincts. But before one rejects the idea as purely superstitious, consider the close connection between people and portraits. Some kind of special relationship is universally felt to exist between the two, for instance, such that even adults plant kisses on images, carry them like champions through the streets, are excited by them – or as angered by them – as they might be by living beings. You don't see the same thing happening with still lifes.</p><p>Dürer, whose 1500 self-portrait has inspired both love and fear down the centuries, may be right to argue that works of art cannot be responsible for acts of human violence. But it's wrong to think that art does not have the strength to move or provoke, to enrage or inspire, and not just admiration but passion or loathing. The attacker acts upon these feelings, inexcusably, but he or she is reacting to something that many people (and indeed many museums) ignore, namely the power of art to affect us.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418866693|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|1ebe4202a935b054b93f3fbeab044fed998a9092 -->",
