      "id":"artanddesign/2013/oct/06/christ-church-spitalfields-dispute-school",
      "sectionId":"artanddesign",
      "sectionName":"Art and design",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T23:04:02Z",
      "webTitle":"The unholy row over Hawksmoor's London masterpiece",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/06/christ-church-spitalfields-dispute-school",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/06/christ-church-spitalfields-dispute-school",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"28",
        "trailText":"<p>Christ Church, Spitalfields is one of the capital's greatest buildings. Now a row over a neighbouring school extension is heading for the courts, writes <strong>Rowan Moore</strong></p>",
        "headline":"The unholy row over Hawksmoor's London masterpiece",
        "body":"<p>A new building for an inner-city primary school is completed, an addition to its premises that is for the use of nursery-age children and is also meant to serve as a community centre for the adult population. The project is a collaboration between the diocese of London, an Anglican rector, and a school whose children are mostly Muslim. The building has been designed by respected architects who won the commission in a competition, and has been approved by planners and English Heritage. Yet the building stands empty and unused, because a group of local residents and architectural experts, assisted by its lawyers, argues that it breaches acts of parliament. They would, ideally, like the new building to be demolished, and years of work and about £1m worth of construction to be binned.</p><p>This seems incomprehensible, coming – as it does – from a group of serious, well-intentioned people; but this is an unusual location: the new building at Christ Church primary stands, like a dinghy beside a liner, next to the sheer white, south elevation of Nicholas Hawksmoor's <a href=\"http://www.spitalfieldsvenue.org/\" title=\"\">Christ Church, Spitalfields</a>, one of the greatest – most powerful, most original, most moving – architectural creations in London. The school building, say the <a href=\"https://www.christchurchspitalfields.org/\" title=\"\">Friends of Christ Church</a>, defaces the setting of Hawksmoor's work, which has been carefully and expensively restored. The view of its south wall, they say, should be unobstructed. They also object to the fact that it stands in what was once the church's graveyard, and later became public gardens, and that it occupies what should be open space.</p><p>This spot has been built on before – a 70s youth centre was demolished to make way for the school building. But, say the Friends, this youth centre was only ever intended to be temporary (this point is disputed) and should not be used as a precedent for a permanent structure. As the Friends have led the campaign which raised many millions to restore the church, they feel their views matter. One of them describes the diocese's actions as \"parking their tanks on our lawn\". Their anger seems personal, as if their own property had been infringed.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419113794'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/10/4/1380913604144/Christ-Church-Spitalfield-001.jpg' alt='Christ Church Spitalfields' width='460' height='298' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>The front aspect of Hawksmoor's Spitalfields church. Photograph: Antonio Olmos</figcaption></figure><p>Claims and counterclaims fly. The building is a \"vanity project\" say the Friends, and there is no need for its community space; the diocese's response is \"we're trying to provide the opportunities that children and families deserve\". The school might close soon, say the Friends; not so, says the diocese. The Friends say they were consulted too little and too late; the diocese says \"there was an enormous amount of consultation\".</p><p>The objectors have on their side the Hawksmoor expert Professor Kerry Downes, Christopher Woodward, co-author of <em>A Guide to the Architecture of London</em>, and Eleanor Mitchell, the architect of the 70s youth centre. They have opposed the project for three years, objecting unsuccessfully as it passed through planning, and are now mounting a legal challenge. They claim the construction contravenes the Open Spaces Act and Disused Burial Grounds Act, and that the last breach is a criminal offence. The diocese of London, the London borough of Tower Hamlets, and the rector of Christ Church, say the Friends, had no right to build, or permit to be built, anything on the site, and they are going to court to try to prove it.</p><p>Yet visiting the empty building, I fail to share their outrage. In itself it is a well-made, well-considered work – a \"barn\", as its architects call it, that rises from a low perimeter, scaled to the size of infants, to a spacious central hall. It has a satisfyingly sturdy timber structure, and big glass walls that afford views through to the surrounding greenery. It is both protective and open, intimate and generous. It also uses materials such as re used stock bricks, with a plum tinge, laid with a garden wall bond. This is an attempt to echo the old walls and houses that huddle close to this and other Hawksmoor churches.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419113796'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/10/3/1380801125633/spitalfields-2-001.jpg' alt='spitalfields 2' width='460' height='275' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>The school's airy, light interior. Photograph: Studio Cullinan and Buck Architects Ltd</figcaption></figure><p>The architects of the project, Jon Buck and Dominic Cullinan of <a href=\"http://www.scabal.net/\" title=\"\">Scabal</a>, argue that its controversial position is the best available. Yes, they could have built it on a bit of playground, squeezing it between mature plane trees and the windows of adjoining properties, but this would have meant laying replacement play areas, with artificial sports pitches and metal fences, at the feet of the church. More important, they say, the place chosen means that the new building can act as both a boundary and portal for the school. It protects the play spaces, but also welcomes people approaching from the side of the churchyard gardens.</p><p>The core of the matter, architecturally, is whether the flank walls of Hawksmoor's churches are set pieces that demand to be seen completely unimpeded, and whether their relationship to their graveyards is an essential and unalterable part of their concept. I would say not: while the buildings themselves are determined and consistent, their surroundings, including those of Christ Church, have always been more loose and elastic. Open space has expanded and contracted, neighbouring buildings have come and gone – the force of the white stone churches lies in their persistence among change.</p><p>As for the argument about open space, it might indeed have been questionable to build something new on what had previously been green, but the existence for 40 years of another structure, the youth centre, does make a difference, and it is arguable whether some more grass or asphalt would be of greater public benefit than what is now being offered.</p><p>The objectors (some of whom know more about Hawksmoor than I do) disagree, and theirs are valid opinions. They have been aired through the processes of planning permission, although they did not prevail. The Friends also have a right to point out that they think public authorities have acted illegally, and if they have a case the courts should examine it. But the point at which they press for demolition is the one at which their campaign looks merciless. There are greater outrages against the fabric of British cities with which to do battle.</p><p>As for the old graveyard of Christ Church, what it requires now is coherent transformation of its landscaping, within which the new school building might stand as a pavilion. Rather than fight legal battles, the Friends, the diocese and other interested parties should concentrate on achieving this.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418956526|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|47564039f6c60bc7bab44a84158d9c6a987bb4ec -->",
