      "id":"artanddesign/2013/oct/05/war-artist-attack-frieze-art-fair",
      "sectionId":"artanddesign",
      "sectionName":"Art and design",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T19:32:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Top British war artist launches assault on 'elite' Frieze art fair",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/05/war-artist-attack-frieze-art-fair",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/05/war-artist-attack-frieze-art-fair",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"9",
        "trailText":"Many established art world names never get a look-in at London art fair, claims official war artist John Keane",
        "headline":"Top British war artist launches assault on 'elite' Frieze art fair",
        "body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://friezelondon.com\" title=\"\">Frieze art fair</a>, which opens for business next week, is a success story for its founders, for artists and for commercial galleries. But those artists and galleries who are consistently left out of the annual event complain it creates a chill wind for everyone else.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.johnkeaneart.com/mainframes.html\" title=\"\">John Keane</a>, who was appointed as the official Gulf war artist by the Imperial War Museum in 1994, believes that Frieze is too selective and has an unhealthy relationship with the contemporary art establishment, particularly Tate Modern. There is now an inner circle, he argues, that puts other visual artists at a disadvantage.</p><p>\"While Frieze is going on it is hard for anyone else to be seen,\" he said this weekend. \"All the newspapers cover the same shows and you tend to see the same artists' names coming up at the Tate, Hayward and Whitechapel galleries.\"</p><p>Keane, who is probably best known for his 2002 <a href=\"http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw57442/Mo-Mowlam\" title=\"\">portrait</a> of the late politician Mo Mowlam, which hangs in the National Portrait Gallery, believes that the system allows a small group of private galleries to benefit from the public support of a nationally funded gallery, such as Tate Modern, that receives money each year to buy new work at the fair.</p><p>\"It is almost like a supermarket sweep,\" said Keane. \"The Tate is allowed in early to look for the best stuff. It might be exciting, and I congratulate Frieze for becoming so successful, but if you happen to be outside the loop it doesn't look quite so good.\"</p><p>Frieze began 11 years ago and takes place every autumn in Regent's Park, London. It has since branched out, with an annual venture in New York starting two years ago and a sister show, Frieze Masters, that allows galleries to sell work from previous eras.</p><p>\"I have never had any work in the show, although I have been working as an artist for a long time now and making a reasonable living. I have a good relationship with a gallery too,\" said Keane, who shows his work at the Flowers Gallery, where his exhibition Fear opens on 19 October. It was inspired by Simon Sebag Montefiore's book about Stalin, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jul/20/biography.features\" title=\"\"><em>The Court of the Red Tsar</em></a>, and Keane believes it is some of the best work he has created.</p><p>The Flowers Gallery was established in 1970 by Angela Flowers and it has never been included in Frieze, despite having applied several times. \"My gallery has been told not to bother applying any more,\" said Keane. \"As I say, it is to its credit that Frieze has been a huge success. The trouble is it pretty much soaks up all the interest and no one else gets coverage.\"</p><p>For Matthew Slotover, the co-founder of Frieze, Keane's charges are undeserved. Slotover, who does not vote on which galleries are included in the fair, believes there is an effort to present a cross-section of the best.</p><p>\"The fair is open to everyone to apply, and we have a changing committee from around the world who decide who is accepted – and we get more than three times the number of applicants to accepted galleries,\" he said. \"The make-up of the fair does change each year, so I always encourage people to apply.\"</p><p>On 17 October the Tate will reveal the works it has bought from this year's fair through the <a href=\"http://friezelondon.com/tate-fund/\" title=\"\">Outset/Frieze art fair fund</a> at a special event held in Tate Britain. The fund was founded in 2003 to support new art and is sponsored by Le Méridien Hotels &amp; Resorts, with extra funding this year from Leviev Extraordinary Diamonds. Each year guest curators from abroad join four Tate curators to help in the selection process.</p><p>\"Outset's work in championing emerging and re-emerging artists has become a vital component of the contemporary art world,\" said the Tate's director, Nicholas Serota, last week.</p><p>Slotover says there is no formal relationship between the Tate and Frieze: \"Tate is given £150,000 from Outset to buy works directly from galleries at Frieze. These are chosen by two independent museum curators in association with Tate.\"</p><p>He points out that art museums often buy works from Frieze, as well as from other fairs such as <a href=\"http://www.tefaf.com/\" title=\"\">Tefaf</a> and<a href=\"https://www.artbasel.com/\" title=\"\"> Art Basel</a>, and that the Tate still buys most of its acquisitions elsewhere.</p><p>Keane, however, believes that many artists feel they are excluded from a privileged group. As an artist who is drawn to political subject matters, he is used, he said, to feeling outside the loop.</p><p>\"Because Frieze is selective it means that money for Outset is spent on an exclusive club. I think this limits plurality,\" Keane said. \"What I would like to ask Matthew Slotover is: 'Can I join your exclusive club, please?'\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419140104|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|653b860b77d41a269c089283a82fa49a05e8dbc2 -->",
