      "id":"artanddesign/2013/oct/04/new-museum-york-security-gold-display",
      "sectionId":"artanddesign",
      "sectionName":"Art and design",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-04T10:40:50Z",
      "webTitle":"New York museum ups security as gold bar sculpture goes on show",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/04/new-museum-york-security-gold-display",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/2013/oct/04/new-museum-york-security-gold-display",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>The Tower of Power has a 24-hour security detail. And it's just one of many controversial pieces in the retrospective of Chris Burden, who's best known for being shot in the name of art</p>",
        "headline":"New York museum ups security as gold bar sculpture goes on show",
        "body":"<p>Every art museum needs guards. But at the <a href=\"http://www.newmuseum.org/\" title=\"\">New Museum in New York</a>, a work by the artist Chris Burden requires security of an especially intense variety.</p><p><a href=\"http://referentiel.nouvelobs.com/file/1215685.jpg\" title=\"\">Tower of Power</a>, a 1985 sculpture now on show in the long-awaited Burden retrospective, consists of 100 kilograms of gold ingots – worth, at today's prices, about £2.6m – stacked in a small pyramid and encased in a vitrine. Surrounding the gold are tiny figures made of matchsticks and sewing needles, encircling the tower like worshippers. The pyramid is barely a foot tall, and it's placed on a modest pedestal that puts the gold below eye level.</p><p>The curators have installed Tower of Power in one of the museum's least visible locations: a tiny niche on a stairwell between the third and fourth floors. Visitors are only allowed up one at a time and must deposit their coats and bags in a locker beforehand. At a press preview this week, an affable private guard – wearing not a New Museum uniform but a dark blue polo shirt with the word \"SECURITY\" emblazoned on it – stood watch. The New Museum will station someone there 24 hours a day.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/chris-burden-extreme-measures\" title=\"\">Chris Burden: Extreme Measures</a>, which opens to the public this weekend, is the first major exhibition of the transgressive Los Angeles artist in the United States in 25 years. The show takes up the entirety of the New Museum's building and has posed logistical challenges even beyond the defense of 100 kilos of bullion.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.boweryboogie.com/2013/09/new-museum-unveils-chris-burden-ghost-ship-facade/\" title=\"\">Dangling on the facade of the museum is Ghost Ship (2005)</a>, a 30ft schooner originally designed to sail unmanned, guided by a computer program. The vessel will remain in place for a year. Also disrupting the exterior is a new work: <a href=\"http://newmuseum.tumblr.com/post/62900262358/opening-today-chris-burden-extreme-measures\" title=\"\">a pair of 36ft towers affixed to the roof</a>. Their incomplete design suggests the breakneck construction of the New Museum's gentrifying neighbourhood and the Twin Towers that once stood just to the south. The structures were installed with a crane that reached from the street all the way to the top of the museum, and the title of the new work – Twin Quasi Legal Skyscrapers – hints at the challenges Burden's art has posed to the institution.</p><p>Elsewhere in the exhibition, viewers will encounter a 1964 Ford crane truck with a one-ton weight suspended from an apparatus mounted on the vehicle's flatbed. <a href=\"http://newmuseum.tumblr.com/post/61783002478/chris-burdens-1-ton-crane-truck-2009-is-now\" title=\"\">One Ton Crane Truck (2009)</a> is on the ground floor because curators were unable to transport it upstairs.</p><p>A giant kinetic sculpture, <a href=\"http://moca.org/pc/viewArtWork.php?id=4\" title=\"\">The Big Wheel (1979)</a>, is a three-ton, 8ft flywheel powered by a 1968 Benelli motorcycle. When a gallery assistant revs the motorcycle's engine, the flywheel starts spinning: at first slowly, then disconcertingly fast. According to the museum, the giant cast-iron flywheel can hit 200 revolutions a minute.</p><p>Burden first came to prominence in the 1970s with videotaped performances of uncommon bravery, or recklessness: <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=26R9KFdt5aY\" title=\"\">having a friend shoot him in the arm with a rifle</a> (Shoot, 1971), or <a href=\"http://www.zwirnerandwirth.com/exhibitions/2004/0904Burden/transfixed.html\" title=\"\">having himself crucified on the bonnet of a Volkswagen Beetle</a> (Trans-Fixed, 1974). The new retrospective features these works only through printed documentation, although, in a videotaped interview, the artist discusses the risks and relevance of his early performances. Asked whether Shoot was anything more than a foolhardy gesture, Burden counters, \"Being shot is as American as apple pie.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419041256|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|106da72140748b92588b4fd2952f8794b672aef0 -->",
